The paper discusses the extension of Feature Markov Decision Processes (PhiMDPs) to Dynamic Bayesian Networks (DBNs), which are commonly used for large-scale real-world problems. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a cost criterion to extract relevant features from the environment, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the building blocks required for a complete general learning algorithm, which suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
